If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we can define a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by declaring 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\sim x\text{ for all }x\in X\text{ and }x\sim y\text{ for all }x,y\in A.
\]

\end_inset

This is an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We say that the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

 is obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\series bold
identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to a point
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

